Here's the registration pattern:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service — one shared HttpClient/state across the app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — new instance per navigation so each page gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so each navigation push creates a new page
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient` and shared state (auth tokens, cache). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps state consistent. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation should get a fresh VM — no stale data from a previous visit. |
| Pages | **Transient** | MAUI Shell creates pages per navigation; transient ensures each push gets a clean page bound to its own VM. |

**Key rules of thumb:**

- **Singleton** → stateful services shared app-wide (HTTP clients, caches, settings).
- **Transient** → UI-layer objects (pages, ViewModels) that should reset per use.
- **Scoped** → rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET), but useful if you create your own `IServiceScope` for a multi-step workflow.

> ⚠️ Never inject a **transient** or **scoped** service into a **singleton** — the shorter-lived service gets captured and effectively becomes a singleton too (the "captive dependency" problem).
